<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-converting-non-linear-equations-into-a-linear-form" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Converting Non-Linear Equations into a Linear Form</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurement and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.6 Graphical Methods
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title> 
                    <p>
                        Convert nonlinear equation to linear form in different situations
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        11
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>

    <!-- [LP] Add guidance on structured lesson plan-->

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    20 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To discover that non-linear relationships can be transformed into straight lines by changing the variables on the axes.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Provide students with a set of data that follows a power law (e.g., $y = ax^2$). Guide them to plot $y$ against $x$ first, then $y$ against $x^2$. Ask them to compare the two graphs.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <activity>
        <statement>
            <p>
                <alert>Work in Groups</alert>
            </p>
            <p>
                A physics student measured the distance, <m>d</m> (in meters), a ball dropped from rest traveled over time, <m>t</m> (in seconds). The data is shown below:
            </p>
            <tabular bottom="minor" top="minor" left="minor" right="minor">
                <row><cell>Time <m>t</m> (s)</cell><cell>1</cell><cell>2</cell><cell>3</cell><cell>4</cell><cell>5</cell></row>
                <row><cell>Distance <m>d</m> (m)</cell><cell>4.9</cell><cell>19.6</cell><cell>44.1</cell><cell>78.4</cell><cell>122.5</cell></row>
            </tabular>
            <p>
                <alert>What to do:</alert>
                <ol>
                    <li><p>Plot a graph of <m>d</m> against <m>t</m>. Describe the shape of the graph.</p></li>
                    <li><p>Create a third row in the table for <m>t^2</m>. Calculate the values.</p></li>
                    <li><p>Plot a graph of <m>d</m> against <m>t^2</m>. What do you notice about this graph?</p></li>
                    <li><p>Draw a line of best fit for the second graph and find its gradient. What does this gradient represent if the relationship is <m>d = \frac{1}{2}gt^2</m>?</p></li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </activity>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Structured Instruction</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To formalize the methods of using logarithms and algebraic manipulation to linearize equations.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Key Takeaways &amp; Teacher Connection</title>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Connecting to Learner Work:</alert> In the activity, students saw that plotting <m>d</m> against <m>t^2</m> turned a curve into a straight line. This is the essence of linearization: finding variables <m>Y</m> and <m>X</m> such that <m>Y = mX + c</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>

    <insight>
        <p>
            To convert a non-linear equation into the linear form <m>Y = mX + c</m>, we use two main techniques:
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Algebraic Manipulation:</alert> Rearranging the equation so that it matches the form <m>Y = mX + c</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Logarithmic Transformation:</alert> Applying <m>\log</m> to both sides of equations like <m>y = ax^n</m> or <m>y = ab^x</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <tabular halign="center" bottom="minor" top="minor" left="minor" right="minor">
            <row>
                <cell>Non-linear Equation</cell>
                <cell>Transformed Linear Equation</cell>
                <cell>Y-axis (<m>Y</m>)</cell>
                <cell>X-axis (<m>X</m>)</cell>
                <cell>Gradient (m)</cell>
                <cell>Intercept (c)</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell><m>y = ax^2+b</m></cell>
                <cell><m>Y = mX + c</m></cell>
                <cell><m>y</m> </cell>
                <cell><m>x^2</m></cell>
                <cell><m>a</m></cell>
                <cell><m>b</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell><m>y = ab^x</m></cell>
                <cell><m>\log y = (\log b)x + \log a</m></cell>
                <cell><m>\log y</m></cell>
                <cell><m>x</m></cell>
                <cell><m>\log b</m></cell>
                <cell><m>\log a</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell><m>y = ax^n</m></cell>
                <cell><m>\log y = n\log x + \log a</m></cell>
                <cell><m>\log y</m></cell>
                <cell><m>\log x</m></cell>
                <cell><m>n</m></cell>
                <cell><m>\log a</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell><m>y = \frac{a}{x} + bx</m></cell>
                <cell><m>xy = a + bx^2</m></cell>
                <cell><m>xy</m></cell>
                <cell><m>x^2</m></cell>
                <cell><m>b</m></cell>
                <cell><m>a</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                    <cell><m>y = ax + \frac{b}{x}</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>xy = ax^2 + b</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>xy</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>x^2</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>a</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>b</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>\frac{1}{y} = ax + b</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>\frac{1}{y} = a(x) + b</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>\frac{1}{y}</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>x</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>a</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>b</m></cell>
                </row>
        </tabular>
    </insight>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                The variables <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> are related by the equation <m>y = ax^n</m>. 
                <ol>
                    <li><p>Express the equation in the linear form <m>Y = mX + c</m>.</p></li>
                    <li><p>A graph of <m>\log_{10} y</m> against <m>\log_{10} x</m> is a straight line with a gradient of 2 and a vertical intercept of 0.602. Calculate the values of <m>a</m> and <m>n</m>.</p></li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Take logs on both sides: <me>\log_{10} y = \log_{10}(ax^n) \implies \log_{10} y = n\log_{10} x + \log_{10} a</me>
                            This is in the form <m>Y = mX + c</m> where <m>Y = \log_{10} y</m>, <m>X = \log_{10} x</m>, <m>m = n</m>, and <m>c = \log_{10} a</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            From the graph:
                            <ul>
                                <li><p>Gradient <m>m = n = 2</m>.</p></li>
                                <li><p>Intercept <m>c = \log_{10} a = 0.602</m>.</p></li>
                            </ul>
                            To find <m>a</m>, take the antilog:
                            <me>a = 10^{0.602} \approx 4</me>
                            Therefore, <m>n = 2</m> and <m>a = 4</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                The population <m>P</m> of a certain bacteria culture after <m>t</m> hours is modeled by <m>P = Ab^t</m>. 
                A biologist plots <m>\ln P</m> against <m>t</m> and obtains a straight line passing through the points <m>(0, 4.605)</m> and <m>(5, 6.105)</m>. 
                Determine the values of <m>A</m> and <m>b</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Linearize the equation:
                <me>\ln P = \ln(Ab^t) \implies \ln P = t\ln b + \ln A</me>
                This is a line with <m>Y = \ln P</m>, <m>X = t</m>, gradient <m>m = \ln b</m>, and intercept <m>c = \ln A</m>.
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Find the intercept <m>c</m>: From the point <m>(0, 4.605)</m>, <m>c = \ln A = 4.605</m>.
                            <me>A = e^{4.605} \approx 100</me>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Find the gradient <m>m</m>:
                            <me>m = \frac{6.105 - 4.605}{5 - 0} = \frac{1.5}{5} = 0.3</me>
                            Since <m>m = \ln b = 0.3</m>:
                            <me>b = e^{0.3} \approx 1.35</me>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                The constants are <m>A = 100</m> and <m>b = 1.35</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Transform the equation <m>y = \frac{x}{ax + b}</m> into a linear form. State the variables to be plotted on the axes and what the gradient and intercept represent.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                The equation is <m>y = \frac{x}{ax + b}</m>. Take the reciprocal of both sides:
                <me>\frac{1}{y} = \frac{ax + b}{x}</me>
                Simplify the fraction:
                <me>\frac{1}{y} = \frac{ax}{x} + \frac{b}{x}</me>
                <me>\frac{1}{y} = b\left(\frac{1}{x}\right) + a</me>
                This is in the form <m>Y = mX + c</m>:
                <ul>
                    <li><p>Plot <m>\frac{1}{y}</m> on the Y-axis.</p></li>
                    <li><p>Plot <m>\frac{1}{x}</m> on the X-axis.</p></li>
                    <li><p>The gradient <m>m</m> is <m>b</m>.</p></li>
                    <li><p>The y-intercept <m>c</m> is <m>a</m>.</p></li>
                </ul>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                The variables <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> are related by
            </p>
            <p>
                <me>y = 3x^2 + 2</me>.
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Show how the equation can be written in a linear form
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            State clearly which variables should be plotted to obtain a straight-line graph
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            State the gradient and intercept of the line in terms of the constants in the equation.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The equation is already in the form <m>y = mx + c</m>, but it is not linear because of the <m>x^2</m> term. 
                            To linearize it, we can let <m>X = x^2</m>. 
                            Then the equation becomes <me>Y = 3X + 2</me>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            To obtain a straight-line graph, plot <m>y</m> on the Y-axis and <m>x^2</m> on the X-axis.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The gradient of the line is 3, and the intercept is 2.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>

    </example>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/assessment-intro.ptx" />

    <exercises>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    For each of the following equations, state the variables that should be plotted to obtain a straight line, and express the gradient and intercept in terms of the constants:
                    <ol>
                        <li><m>y = ax^2 + bx</m></li>
                        <li><m>y = p\sqrt{x} + q</m></li>
                        <li><m>xy = a^x + b</m> (Assume <m>b</m> is known)</li>
                        <li><m>y = \frac{a}{x^2} + b</m></li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <ol>
                        <li><p>Divide by <m>x</m>: <m>\frac{y}{x} = ax + b</m>. Plot <m>\frac{y}{x}</m> vs <m>x</m>. <m>m=a, c=b</m>.</p></li>
                        <li><p>Plot <m>y</m> vs <m>\sqrt{x}</m>. <m>m=p, c=q</m>.</p></li>
                        <li><p><m>\log_{10}(xy - b) = x \log_{10} a</m>. Plot <m>\log_{10}(xy - b)</m> vs <m>x</m>. <m>m=\log_{10} a, c=0</m>.</p></li>
                        <li><p>Plot <m>y</m> vs <m>\frac{1}{x^2}</m>. <m>m=a, c=b</m>.</p></li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A graph of <m>y/x</m> against <m>x</m> is a straight line passing through <m>(2, 5)</m> and <m>(6, 13)</m>. 
                    <ol>
                        <li><p>Find the equation of the line in terms of <m>y</m> and <m>x</m>.</p></li>
                        <li><p>Express <m>y</m> explicitly in terms of <m>x</m>.</p></li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Gradient <m>m = \frac{13 - 5}{6 - 2} = \frac{8}{4} = 2</m>.
                            Intercept: <m>5 = 2(2) + c \implies c = 1</m>.
                            Equation: <m>\frac{y}{x} = 2x + 1</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li><p><m>y = 2x^2 + x</m>.</p></li>
                </ol>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Experimental data follows the law <m>y = \frac{k}{x+a}</m>. 
                    Describe how a straight line can be obtained and how the constants <m>k</m> and <m>a</m> can be found from the graph.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    Take the reciprocal: <m>\frac{1}{y} = \frac{x+a}{k} = \frac{1}{k}x + \frac{a}{k}</m>. 
                    Plot <m>\frac{1}{y}</m> against <m>x</m>. 
                    The gradient is <m>1/k</m>, so <m>k = 1/\text{gradient}</m>. 
                    The intercept is <m>a/k</m>, so <m>a = \text{intercept} \times k</m>.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    The relationship between two variables is given by
                </p>
                <p>
                    <me>y = \frac{2}{x} + 1</me>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Transform the equation into a linear form
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                State clearly the graph that should be drawn to obtain a straight line
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Identify the gradient and y‑intercept of the straight‑line graph
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Take the reciprocal of both sides: <m>\frac{1}{y} = \frac{x}{2} + \frac{1}{2}</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li><p>Plot <m>\frac{1}{y}</m> against <m>x</m>.</p></li>
                    <li><p>Gradient: <m>\frac{1}{2}</m>; y‑intercept: <m>\frac{1}{2}</m>.</p></li>
                </ol>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation</title>

        <table>
            <title>Differentiation</title>
            <tabular halign="left">
                <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                    <cell>Learner Group</cell>
                    <cell>Strategy &amp; Learning Experience</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Struggling Learners (Support)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        Focus on algebraic transformations where logs are not required first (e.g., <m>y = ax^2 + b</m>). Provide a template table for <m>Y</m> and <m>X</m>.
                    </cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>On-Level Learners (Core)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line>The core lesson activities, moving from discovery to formal log-based transformations.</line>
                    </cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Advanced Learners (Challenge)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        Provide complex forms like <m>y = \frac{x}{ax + b}</m> and ask them to determine the linearizing variables (e.g., <m>\frac{1}{y} = a + \frac{b}{x}</m>).
                    </cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </table>
    </axiom>

